[364.228405, "o", "Ah! If the plasmid supplies the start and stop codons, then the gBlock itself should NOT have a start codon at its beginning, nor a stop codon at its end. Or does it mean the whole sequence has no start (ATG) or stop (TAA, TAG, TGA) codons at all? No, internal ATG is definitely allowed because mCherry/Clover have internal methionines (which must be coded by ATG). Also, can there be stop codons in other frames? Usually 'no start or stop codons' in this context means: the sequence has no stop codons in its reading frame (so it is a single open reading frame), and it doesn't start with ATG or end with a stop codon. Let's verify if there can be any internal stop codon (which would terminate translation prematurely, so obviously no stop codons in-frame). What about start codon (ATG)? Can it have internal ATG? Yes, since standard methionines are encoded by ATG. What about ATG at the very start of the gBlock? Since the N-terminal methionine is removed from the first subprotein, the gBlock does not start with ATG.\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r\u001b[?2004h> "]
