[364.23539, "o", "Verification Logic details:\r\n1. Read SOLUTION_DIR (default: /app), VERDICT_FILE (default: /logs/verifier/reward.txt)\r\n2. Read gblock.txt from SOLUTION_DIR\r\n3. Check if gblock.txt exists. If not, write 0 and exit.\r\n4. Read and strip/clean the sequence. Check that it is on a single line and contains only A, T, C, G (case-insensitive? The prompt says 'uses only the DNA bases A, T, C, and G'. Let's convert to uppercase or handle both uppercase/lowercase, but DNA is usually uppercase. Let's make sure it's uppercase/lowercase A,T,C,G and we convert to uppercase for translation).\r\n5. Check length <= 3000.\r\n6. Check every 50-nucleotide window has GC content between 30% and 70%. (Number of G+C divided by 50 is between 0.30 and 0.70 inclusive? Or strictly between? Usually 30% and 70% are inclusive: 15 to 35 GC bases in every 50-nt window. Let's make sure we check all windows of length 50, so indices from 0 to len-50 inclusive).\r\n7. No start or stop codons in the DNA (in any frame? Or in the encoded frame? The prompt says 'No start or stop codons (the plasmid supplies those)'. This means in the reading frame of the gBlock itself!). Let's make sure our translation has no start (M, ATG) or stop (*, TAA, TAG, TGA) in its reading frame!\r\nWait! Let's check: 'No start or stop codons'. This means in the reading frame of the gBlock. So when we translate the gBlock starting at index 0 (reading frame 1), the resulting amino acid sequence must not contain 'M' (start) or '*' (stop) codon. Wait, does a start codon only translate to 'M' (ATG)? Yes. And stop codons are TAA, TAG, TGA which translate to '*'. So the translated amino acid sequence must not contain 'M' or '*'. Let's check if 'M' can appear inside the protein sequence. Wait! Yes, mCherry, Clover, and DHFR contain internal methionines! For example, mCherry has `MVSKGEEDNMAIIKEFMRFKVHME...`. Those internal methionines are coded by ATG. Does 'no start codon' mean there can be no ATG at all, or does it mean the translated protein does not start with a start codon (or have an N-terminal M), or that there is no start codon (ATG) in the reading frame that initiates translation? \r\nLet's re-read carefully:\r\n'No start or stop codons (the plasmid supplies those).'\r\n'The N-terminal methionine is removed from every subprotein (the plasmid supplies it).'\r\nAh! If the plasmid supplies the start and stop codons, then the gBlock itself should NOT have a start codon at its beginning, nor a stop codon at its end. Or does it mean the whole sequence has no start (ATG) or stop (TAA, TAG, TGA) codons at all? No, internal ATG is definitely allowed because mCherry/Clover have internal methionines (which must be coded by ATG). Also, can there be stop codons in other frames? Usually 'no start or stop codons' in this context means: the sequence has no stop codons in its reading frame (so it is a single open reading frame), and it doesn't start with ATG or end with a stop codon. Let's verify if there can be any internal stop codon (which would terminate translation prematurely, so obviously no stop codons in-frame). What about start codon (ATG)? Can it have internal ATG? Yes, since standard methionines are encoded by ATG. What about ATG at the very start of the gBlock? Since the N-terminal methionine is removed from the first subprotein, the gBlock does not start with ATG.\r\nLet's write a script to check this carefully.\r\n"]
